				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\mu }_{MD}$$\end{document}) and interfacial dipole (μID\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\mu }_{ID}$$\end{document}). This transformation of the modified conductors into efficient electron-selective electrodes resulted in devices with superior electrical and photoelectrical properties compared to those of the original MoS2 FETs. Moreover, we found that this polymer surface modifier is an attractive alternative to incorporating chemically reactive low work function metals due to its low cost, large-area scalability, compatibility with environmentally benign solvents, and easy manufacturing process. Thus, our approach has the potential to pave the way for various electrical, photoelectrical, and organic-based electronic technologies.
